Certainly! Here's a C# code snippet that defines sustainability using nested for loops, adhering to your constraints:

```csharp
int sustainabilityScore = 0; 
for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) 
    for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++)
        sustainabilityScore += (i + j) % 2 == 0 ? 1 : -1;
Console.WriteLine(sustainabilityScore);
```

This code calculates a simple sustainability score based on the iteration indices, using two nested for loops and keeping the code concise within 5 lines.
